    ninetyPlusAddition: 'The Snowden precedent: disclosed NSA/GCHQ mass surveillance in 2013, living in exile. The UK\'s reaction was to pass IPA 2016 — partially legitimising what had been happening, while also adding oversight. Lessons: (1) disclosure created democratic accountability that existing oversight failed to provide; (2) it also caused demonstrable national security damage; (3) it revealed that existing oversight mechanisms were inadequate. 90%+ answer: argues that this scenario demonstrates the OVERSIGHT MECHANISM FAILURE that makes the professional dilemma intractable — if IPT were functioning properly, the contractor would not face this choice. The real answer is: fix the oversight system, not criminalise the person who reveals its failure.',
